Graffiti and murals decorate Prishtina's centre 

A city whose walls are canvases 

Meaningful arts throughout the city decorate public spaces, show social protests, raise awareness in social topics, and commemorate. Each graffiti has a scenario with interesting meanings with local and international connotations. 

If you see the cat, smile back

Monsieur Chat, happy yellow graffiti cat, is also seen in Prishtina.

Mr. Chat can be spotted in Prishtina smiling to citizens and adding color to the city. 

    No more "big grey electric boxes"

    Citizens have decided to have fun with something as mundane as the electric boxes

    Honoring Kosovo's artists

    Just as Dua Lipa is proud of Kosovo, so is Kosovo proud of her.

    In one of the main buildings of Kosovo stands the striking mural of Dua Lipa with her outfit from the "Swan Song" where the citizens honored her for all the good she has done for her country.

    The portrait of the Albanian music icon

    Created by two artists from Spain.

    The purpose of this mural is to honor Nexhmije Pagarusha, the nightingale of Albanian music, who left a mark on Albanian culture. 


    Raising awareness!

    Citizens express how they feel about relevant issues on the society. A such small piece of wall is holding words with great importance like how killers should be in jail and how women should not be asked what they were wearing if they were assaulted.

    Occupying the walls for protests

    Who thinks like Xhevdet, acts like Dardan!

    After a young woman was beaten to death by a Kosovar named Dardan, an analysist called Xhevdet reasoned his behavior which led to citizens calling protests and writing such statements on walls.

    Calling for justice

    Graffiti acting as a direct response to government's failures.

    Ukshin Hoti, jailed several times by the Yugoslav authorities for his political activism on behalf of Kosovar Albanians, went missing during the Kosovo war and there are many pieces of graffiti asking for his whereabouts 

    Remembering those who have gone

    Astrit Dehari's face is painted on the wall along with sentences written to him so he is not forgotten. 

    Astrit Dehari, an activist, died in mysterious circumstances in a Prizren jail. The officials said that he committed suicide with a honey bottle, however, people refuse to believe that is the case. 

    Graffiti used to protest that honey bottles are not guns and that is not the reason why Astrit Dehari is now dead.
